\chapter*{Abstract}
\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Abstract}

Adversarial attacks pose a significant threat to the reliability of deep
learning models, particularly in the domain of AI-generated image
classification. This project investigates the vulnerability of AI-generated
images to adversarial attacks using the Fast Gradient Sign Method (FGSM).
The CIFAKE dataset, consisting of 120,000 images (60,000 real and 60,000
AI-generated via Stable Diffusion v1.4), is used to train a Convolutional
Neural Network (CNN) classifier that achieves a baseline test accuracy of
94.53\%, exceeding the published CIFAKE benchmark of 92.98\%.

FGSM attacks are applied across six epsilon values (0.0 to 0.3), resulting in
a maximum accuracy drop of 88.39\% at $\epsilon = 0.1$, where model accuracy
falls to just 6.14\%. A pixel variation-based detection method is proposed
that measures mean absolute pixel differences between clean and adversarial
images using an empirically calibrated threshold of $\tau = 0.0497$, achieving
a 98.5\% detection rate on the benchmark. Prototype testing on internet-sourced
real and AI-generated images confirms cross-domain generalisation without
retraining. A Chrome extension integrated with a local Flask server is also
developed to enable real-time adversarial detection in a web browser.

Our results demonstrate that AI-generated image classifiers are highly
susceptible to adversarial perturbations and that pixel variation analysis
is an effective and computationally lightweight detection technique,
deployable without GPU requirements.

\vspace{0.8cm}
\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} Adversarial Attacks, Fast Gradient Sign Method
(FGSM), AI-Generated Images, Convolutional Neural Network (CNN),
Pixel Variation, CIFAKE Dataset, Deep Learning Security, Image Classification

