\chapter{Introduction}

\section{Introduction}

The past few years have seen the rapid development and integration of
Artificial Intelligence in all sectors of working industries as well as
our daily lives. The most visible rise was seen from 2022, driven by
generative AI tools that require no technical knowledge to use. People
of all age groups rely on generative AI tools for their work and
day-to-day tasks. The accessibility of plain language prompting brought
these technologies to the broader public. However, this widespread
accessibility has also led to a surge in adversarial attacks. The changes
introduced by such attacks are often invisible to the user: the result may
appear completely normal or identical to the original data, while the AI
model has been completely deceived. Even highly trained models can have
blind spots, and attackers exploit these vulnerabilities to manipulate
model predictions with high confidence.

Adversarial attacks were popularised and formally studied by Ian Goodfellow,
who introduced the Fast Gradient Sign Method
(FGSM)~\cite{goodfellow2015}. In his work, he illustrated how adding
small perturbations computed from the gradient of the loss function could
cause a model to misclassify a panda image as a gibbon with 99.3\%
confidence. The FGSM attack operates according to the formula:

\begin{equation}
x_{adv} = x + \epsilon \cdot \text{sign}(\nabla_{x} J(\theta, x, y))
\label{eq:fgsm}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $x$ is the input image, $\epsilon$ is the perturbation
magnitude, $J$ is the loss function, and $\theta$ represents the model
parameters. The adversarial image may appear unchanged to the user but
contains enough disturbance to cause the model to misclassify the data.

\section{Problem Statement}

AI-generated image classifiers trained on datasets such as CIFAKE are
highly effective under normal conditions but remain fundamentally
vulnerable to adversarial inputs. A single-step gradient-based attack such
as FGSM can reduce a classifier's accuracy from over 94\% to below 7\%
without any visible change to the input image. Existing detection methods
often require separate neural networks, model retraining, or
computationally expensive frequency domain transformations, limiting their
practicality for real-world deployment on consumer hardware.

\section{Project Objectives}

This project addresses three key objectives:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Investigate the vulnerability of AI-generated image classifiers
    to FGSM adversarial attacks across a range of epsilon values on the
    CIFAKE benchmark.
    \item Propose and validate a computationally lightweight pixel
    variation-based detection method using a calibrated threshold
    $\tau = 0.0497$ that requires no separate model, no retraining, and
    no frequency domain transformation.
    \item Validate the system on real-world internet-sourced images and
    deploy a prototype Chrome extension for browser-based adversarial
    image detection powered by the trained CNN model running locally.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Project Methodology}

The project follows a systematic four-stage pipeline:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Data Preparation}: The CIFAKE dataset of 120,000 images
    is preprocessed through resize, tensor conversion, and normalisation
    to $[-1, 1]$.
    \item \textbf{Model Training}: A custom CNN with three convolutional
    blocks and fully connected layers is trained on CIFAKE for 10 epochs
    using Adam optimiser and Cross-Entropy loss on an NVIDIA RTX 3050
    Laptop GPU.
    \item \textbf{Adversarial Attack}: FGSM is applied across six epsilon
    values, generating adversarial examples and evaluating accuracy
    degradation.
    \item \textbf{Detection}: Pixel variation analysis with threshold
    $\tau = 0.0497$ detects adversarial perturbations with 98.5\%
    accuracy, validated on both CIFAKE and real-world prototype images.
\end{itemize}

