\chapter{Literature Review}

\section{Explaining and Harnessing Adversarial Examples}

Ian J. Goodfellow, Jonathan Shlens, and Christian Szegedy
(2015)~\cite{goodfellow2015} introduced the Fast Gradient Sign Method in
their paper ``Explaining and Harnessing Adversarial Examples,'' which laid
the foundational work for research on adversarial attacks. They demonstrated
that the root cause of adversarial vulnerabilities lies in the linear nature
of models in high-dimensional spaces: invisible changes to individual pixels
can cause the model to give a wrong prediction. The authors illustrated this
with an example where an imperceptible layer of noise was added to an image
of a panda, causing GoogleNet to incorrectly label it as a gibbon with 99.3\%
confidence. The study also proposed adversarial training as a defence
mechanism, though models still retained high confidence in wrong predictions
when under attack.

\section{Detecting Adversarial Examples Utilizing Pixel Value Diversity}

Jinxin Dong and Pingqiang Zhou~\cite{dong2024} proposed an adversarial
detection framework based on pixel value diversity. Their core observation
was that adversarial perturbations produce consistent and measurable changes
in the statistical distribution of pixel values, converting repetitive pixels
into unique ones. Two metrics were introduced: the Unique Pixel Value Ratio
(UPVR) and Repetitive Pixel Value Ratio (RPVR). Detection was performed
using threshold-based and Bayesian classifier methods, tested across MNIST,
CIFAR-10, and ImageNet against FGSM, CW, PGD, BIM, DeepFool, and Boundary
attacks. Their approach achieved AUC scores between 97\% and 100\%, outperforming the LID detection method across all benchmarks.

\section{Vulnerabilities in AI-Generated Image Detection}

Diao et al.~\cite{diao2026} conducted a comprehensive study on the
adversarial robustness of AI-generated image detectors. The authors
observed that real and AI-generated images have significant differences in
the frequency domain, and designed a Frequency-based Post-train Bayesian
Attack (FPBA). Their approach introduced perturbations via Discrete Cosine
Transform (DCT) combined with a post-train Bayesian strategy that appends
lightweight components to a frozen surrogate model, achieving a white-box
success rate of 99.6\% and a black-box transfer rate of 50.5\%. The study
also found that traditional adversarial training failed to improve robustness
as a defence mechanism.

\section{CIFAKE Dataset}

Bird and Lotfi~\cite{bird2024} introduced the CIFAKE dataset as a benchmark
for distinguishing real photographs from AI-generated images. It pairs
CIFAR-10 real images with Stable Diffusion v1.4 synthetic images at
32$\times$32 resolution. The published baseline achieved 92.98\% accuracy.
The dataset provides an ideal benchmark for studying adversarial
vulnerabilities in AI-generated image classifiers.

\section{Additional Related Work}

AL Roken et al.~\cite{alroken2025} provided a comprehensive taxonomy and
review of adversarial attack detection in the AI era, covering
fundamentals, detection categories, and open challenges across vision and
language models. Ryu and Choi~\cite{ryu2024} proposed an adversarial
detection method based on differences in image entropy, achieving reliable
detection across FGSM and PGD attacks. Mavali et al.~\cite{mavali2025}
studied the adversarial robustness of AI-generated image detectors in
real-world settings, highlighting the gap between benchmark and
deployment performance. Xu et al.~\cite{xu2020} provided a broad review
of adversarial attacks and defences in images, graphs, and text.

