\chapter{Methodology}

\section{System Overview}

The proposed system addresses adversarial attack detection in AI-generated
image classification through a three-stage pipeline: (i) baseline model
training, (ii) adversarial example generation via FGSM, and (iii) pixel
variation-based detection. Each stage is designed to be computationally
lightweight and reproducible without specialised hardware beyond a
consumer-grade GPU.

A CNN trained to distinguish real from AI-generated images provides a
robust baseline classifier. Adversarial examples are then generated by
exploiting the gradient of the model's loss function with respect to the
input image via the FGSM paradigm. Rather than deploying a second neural
network as a detector, the system exploits the fact that FGSM-perturbed
images carry measurable pixel-level signatures that are statistically
distinguishable from clean images using a simple threshold rule.

\section{Data Preprocessing and Loading}

Raw images from the CIFAKE dataset undergo the following preprocessing
pipeline before being fed to the CNN:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Resize}: Images are resized to 32$\times$32 pixels
    using bilinear interpolation, ensuring consistency when the pipeline
    is extended to external images of varying dimensions.
    \item \textbf{Tensor conversion}: Each image is converted from a PIL
    Image (integer pixel values in $[0, 255]$) to a PyTorch tensor with
    float values in $[0.0, 1.0]$ using \texttt{transforms.ToTensor()}.
    \item \textbf{Normalisation}: Pixel values are normalised channel-wise
    using mean $\mu = [0.5, 0.5, 0.5]$ and standard deviation
    $\sigma = [0.5, 0.5, 0.5]$, mapping the range from $[0,1]$ to
    $[-1, 1]$:
    \begin{equation}
        x_{norm} = \frac{x - 0.5}{0.5}
        \label{eq:norm}
    \end{equation}
\end{enumerate}

The complete preprocessing pipeline is:
\begin{equation}
    \tilde{x} = \text{Norm}(\text{ToTensor}(\text{Resize}(x_{raw})))
    \label{eq:preprocess}
\end{equation}

