\section{CNN Architecture}

A custom CNN was designed in PyTorch for binary classification of real
versus AI-generated images. The architecture follows a standard encoder
pattern with three convolutional blocks followed by fully connected
classification layers.

\textbf{Convolutional blocks}: Three successive blocks extract
progressively abstract spatial features. The first block uses 32 filters
to capture low-level texture and edge features, the second uses 64 filters
for mid-level structural patterns, and the third uses 128 filters for
higher-level semantic representations. Each convolutional layer uses a
$3\times3$ kernel with padding~=~1 to preserve spatial dimensions before
pooling.

\textbf{Max-pooling}: A $2\times2$ max-pooling layer after each
convolutional block reduces spatial dimensions by half. After three pooling
operations, the $32\times32$ input is reduced to a $4\times4$ spatial map
with 128 channels, yielding a 2048-dimensional flattened feature vector.

\textbf{Fully connected layers}: The flattened vector passes through a
256-neuron FC layer with ReLU activation and Dropout(0.5), followed by a
2-neuron output layer. Cross-Entropy Loss is used as the training
objective. The Adam optimiser with $\alpha = 0.001$ was selected for its
adaptive gradient scaling. Training was conducted for 10 epochs on an
NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3050 Laptop GPU (4.3~GB VRAM) with batch size 64.

