\section{FGSM Attack Implementation}

The FGSM attack generates adversarial examples by computing the gradient
of the model's loss with respect to the input and taking a single step in
the direction that maximally increases the loss:

\begin{equation}
x_{adv} = \text{clip}\!\left(x + \epsilon \cdot \text{sign}
\!\left(\nabla_{x} J(\theta, x, y)\right),\; -1,\; 1\right)
\label{eq:fgsm_clip}
\end{equation}

Because FGSM uses the sign of the gradient, every pixel is shifted by
exactly $\epsilon$, giving the theoretical bound:

\begin{equation}
|x_{adv} - x| \leq \epsilon \quad \forall\; \text{pixels}
\label{eq:bound}
\end{equation}

This bound is the theoretical foundation for the pixel variation detector.
Gradients are computed using PyTorch autograd with
\texttt{requires\_grad = True}, \texttt{loss.backward()}, and
\texttt{images.grad.data}. Six epsilon values were evaluated:
$\epsilon \in \{0.0, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3\}$.

