\end{figure}

\section{Pixel Variation Detection and Threshold Selection}

Our detection method exploits the bound in Equation~\ref{eq:bound}. The
detection score is the mean absolute pixel difference:

\begin{equation}
S(x, x') = \frac{1}{C \cdot H \cdot W}
\sum_{c,h,w}
\left|x'_{c,h,w} - x_{c,h,w}\right|
\label{eq:pixel_score}
\end{equation}

An image is flagged as adversarial if $S(x,x') > \tau$:

\begin{equation}
\hat{y}_{det} =
\begin{cases}
\text{Adversarial} & \text{if } S(x, x') > \tau \\
\text{Clean}       & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\label{eq:decision}
\end{equation}

The threshold $\tau = 0.0497$ was set empirically at the upper bound of
the observed FGSM pixel difference distribution ($[0.0456, 0.0500]$ at
$\epsilon = 0.05$), maximising specificity while maintaining a 98.5\%
detection rate. The method requires no separate neural network, no
retraining, and no frequency domain transformation, with computational
cost $\mathcal{O}(C \cdot H \cdot W)$ per image pair.

