\section{FGSM Attack Results}

Accuracy drops sharply from 94.53\% (clean) to just \textbf{6.14\%} at
$\epsilon = 0.1$, an 88.39\% degradation. Even the weakest perturbation
at $\epsilon = 0.01$ reduces accuracy by 17.83\%, confirming that the
classifier is highly susceptible across the full epsilon range tested. At
$\epsilon = 0.1$, the model is performing significantly worse than random
chance (50\%), indicating that FGSM has effectively inverted the model's
predictions. The partial accuracy recovery at $\epsilon > 0.1$ is due to
pixel clipping saturation at the $[-1,1]$ boundary, making
$\epsilon \in [0.05, 0.1]$ the most practically dangerous attack range.

\begin{figure}[H]
