\chapter{Prototype Testing on Real-World Images}
\label{sec:prototype}

To validate the practical applicability of the proposed system, we tested
two internet-sourced images entirely outside the CIFAKE dataset. Each
image was resized to $32\times32$, normalised to $[-1,1]$, classified by
the CNN, subjected to FGSM at $\epsilon = 0.05$, and evaluated against
$\tau = 0.0497$. The two cases represent opposite class predictions to
evaluate the threshold's behaviour across both classification outcomes.

\section{Test Case 1: Real Photograph --- Mountain Landscape}

The first image was a real mountain and valley landscape photograph. The
CNN correctly classified it as \textbf{REAL} with 96.0\% confidence.
Following FGSM, the mean pixel difference was \textbf{0.0495} with
standard deviation 0.0048, falling 0.0002 below $\tau = 0.0497$. The
detector correctly returned \textbf{CLEAN}. The heatmap in
Figure~\ref{fig:test_image2} shows a sparse, isolated perturbation
pattern with most pixels at near-zero difference, consistent with the
model's high-confidence prediction producing shallow loss gradients.

