% CHAPTER 7: DISCUSSION
%------------------------------------------------------------
\chapter{Discussion}

\section{Vulnerability of AI-Generated Image Classifiers}

The FGSM experiments confirm that CNN classifiers trained on AI-generated
image datasets are highly vulnerable to adversarial perturbations across
the full epsilon range. The accuracy collapse from 94.53\% to 6.14\% at
$\epsilon = 0.1$ while the perturbation remains completely invisible to
the human eye is a critical security finding. A classifier operating at
6.14\% accuracy is effectively inverted, predicting the wrong class with
high confidence for the vast majority of inputs. Even the weakest tested
attack at $\epsilon = 0.01$ reduces accuracy by 17.83\%, indicating that
real-world content authentication systems face significant risk even from
near-invisible, low-effort adversarial inputs.

\section{Threshold Calibration and Detection Reliability}

The threshold $\tau = 0.0497$ was calibrated empirically at the upper
bound of the observed FGSM adversarial pixel difference distribution
($[0.0456, 0.0500]$ at $\epsilon = 0.05$). A threshold of $\tau = 0.03$
would introduce false positives from image compression artefacts, while
$\tau = 0.05$ would miss adversarial samples in the lower distribution
tail. The selected value of 0.0497 avoids both risks and is validated by
the prototype testing: the real photograph (mean diff 0.0495) is correctly
returned CLEAN, while the AI-generated image (mean diff 0.0498) is
correctly flagged ADVERSARIAL, with the two values differing by only
0.0003.

\section{Interpretation of Prototype Heatmap Patterns}

The contrasting heatmap patterns provide a mechanistic insight into FGSM's
behaviour across image types. A high-confidence prediction (96.0\%)
implies a low Cross-Entropy loss and shallow gradients across most pixels,
producing sparse perturbation and a mean pixel difference (0.0495) just
below $\tau$. A lower-confidence prediction (84.9\%) implies a higher
loss and steeper gradients at the salient foreground, producing
concentrated perturbation and a mean pixel difference (0.0498) just above
$\tau$. This mechanistic link between model confidence, gradient
structure, and pixel difference validates $S(x,x')$ as a physically
interpretable quantity.

\section{Comparison with Related Work}

Our pixel variation detection achieves a 98.5\% detection rate at
$\tau = 0.0497$, comparable to the 98\% reported by Dong and
Zhou~\cite{dong2024} and substantially higher than the 81.42\% reported
by Li et al.~\cite{li2024}. Unlike these approaches, our method requires
no separate detection network, no model retraining, and no frequency
domain transformation. Neither related method was evaluated on AI-generated
image classification specifically, making this work the first to validate
a pixel-level adversarial detector in the CIFAKE domain.

\section{Practical Deployment Considerations}

The pixel variation detector operates at $\mathcal{O}(C \cdot H \cdot W)$
computational cost per image pair, requiring only 3,072 arithmetic
operations for a $32\times32$ RGB image --- orders of magnitude less
expensive than CNN inference. This makes it deployable on CPU-only
hardware, embedded systems, and mobile devices. Cross-domain consistency
confirms that the pixel variation signature of FGSM is a property of the
attack algorithm rather than a dataset-specific artefact.

