\chapter{Conclusion and Future Work}

\section{Conclusion}

This project presented a comprehensive investigation of adversarial attacks
on AI-generated image classifiers using the CIFAKE dataset. The trained
CNN achieved 94.53\% test accuracy, exceeding the published CIFAKE
baseline. FGSM attacks reduced accuracy to as low as 6.14\% at
$\epsilon = 0.1$, confirming severe vulnerability across the full epsilon
range. The proposed pixel variation detector with threshold $\tau = 0.0497$
achieved a \textbf{98.5\% detection rate}, calibrated at the upper bound
of the adversarial distribution to maximise specificity. Real-world
prototype testing on internet-sourced images confirmed correct
classification and detection without retraining, with the threshold
correctly separating adversarial (mean diff 0.0498) from clean (mean
diff 0.0495) images differing by only 0.0003.

Key contributions of this project are as follows:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Experimental FGSM vulnerability analysis on CIFAKE across six
    epsilon values, showing up to 88.39\% accuracy degradation while
    perturbations remain visually imperceptible.
    \item Calibrated pixel variation detector achieving 98.5\% detection
    rate with $\tau = 0.0497$, requiring no additional model or retraining,
    deployable at $\mathcal{O}(C \cdot H \cdot W)$ computational cost.
    \item Comprehensive visualisations including confusion matrices, ROC
    curves, pixel heatmaps, training curves, perturbation visualisation,
    and statistical analysis.
    \item Real-world prototype validation on internet-sourced real and
    AI-generated images confirming cross-domain generalisation.
    \item Chrome extension prototype enabling browser-based real-time
    adversarial image detection powered by the trained model.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Future Work}

Future work includes:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Extended attack evaluation}: Evaluation against PGD,
    CW, DeepFool, and BIM attacks to assess detector generalisation
    beyond FGSM.
    \item \textbf{Adversarial training defences}: Incorporating
    adversarial training into the CNN pipeline to improve model
    robustness against gradient-based attacks.
    \item \textbf{Adaptive threshold selection}: Developing per-image
    adaptive threshold calibration based on model confidence to improve
    detection at the adversarial boundary.
    \item \textbf{Higher-resolution extension}: Extending the pipeline
    to higher-resolution outputs from modern diffusion models such as
    Stable Diffusion XL and Midjourney.
    \item \textbf{Multi-class detection}: Expanding beyond binary
    REAL/FAKE classification to multi-class generative model attribution.
\end{itemize}

